        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-09-07T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-09-07T22:00:00-05:00" n="694"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d694">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1163/724: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-09-08T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >September 8, 1936—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 8—6:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>438. Reference last paragraph Embassy’s despatch number 600, July 24.<note n="49"
                        xml:id="d694fn49">Not printed.</note> The Consulate General at Shanghai in a
                    despatch dated August 28 transmits a news item to the effect that the Nanking
                    Municipal Government will begin on October 1 next the collection of land value
                    taxes on property at Nanking; the collection of such taxes is considered to be
                    the natural step following upon the current re-registration of title deeds. No
                    official notice has been received by the Consulate General regarding the tax.
                        Gauss<note n="50" xml:id="d694fn50">Clarence E. Gauss, Consul General at
                        Shanghai.</note> observes that the land value taxable [<hi rend="italic"
                        >tax?</hi>] is apparently being paid at Shanghai by American and British
                    owners of land in Chinese administered areas, by the former as a “voluntary
                    contribution”, but apparently is not being paid by the Japanese. He states:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I have no particular objection to the rates of proposed land value taxes
                            as reported to have been adopted for Nanking, or as authorized by the
                            land law (section 4); but when we shall have submitted to ‘land value’
                            taxes, we will next be confronted with the ‘increased value’ land taxes
                            (as distinguished from the land tax) as provided for in article 305 of
                            the land law”.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>The instructions of the Department are requested with regard to the policy to be
                    adopted as to the land value tax.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
